within the same utter-        appear in the same utterance but without frequent grammatical\n                                        ance, poses significant challenges for automatic speech recognition      switching. In contrast, our method specifically addresses code-\narXiv:2607.05224v1 [cs.CL] 6 Jul 2026\n\n\n\n\n                                        (ASR) due to limited CS training data. This paper applies an itera-      switching speech which involves more dynamic and spontaneous\n                                        tive pseudo-labeling training approach to CS-ASR for the first time,     alternation between languages. Second, our approach leverages\n                                        demonstrating its effectiveness in leveraging unlabeled data to im-      unlabeled data that we assume to contain code-switching scenarios,\n                                        prove CS-ASR performance. The approach comprises three phases:           whereas prior methods typically rely on monolingual or code-mixing\n                                        pseudo-label generation, two-stage bilingual model training, and it-     datasets that lack such code-switching contexts. Finally, our initial\n                                        erative improvements. It begins by generating pseudo-labels from         ASR model (M0) combines Mandarin and English monolingual data\n                                        a large unlabeled corpus, creating a semi-supervised dataset. This       during training, providing it with a robust understanding of both lan-\n                                        dataset supports a two-stage training framework where the model          guages from the outset. This bilingual initialization sets our method\n                                        is pre-trained and then fine-tuned on supervised CS data. Iterative      apart from previous pseudo-labeling works.\n                                        refinements further enhance the model’s acc